<a name="msg-14081"></a>
<div class="PhorumReadMessageBlock">
<div class="PhorumStdBlock">
<div class="PhorumReadBodySubject"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-2">Re: Ship ownership</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Posted by: </kw><strong><a href="http://www.piratesinfo.com/mysql/phorum/profile.php?1,1667"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Ged Foxe</kw></a></strong><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1"> (---.winn.dial.virgin.net)</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Date: 17 November 2004, 04:08PM</kw></div>
<br>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyText"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3"> Titles like "mate" and "quartermaster" may mean different things at different times.  Of course, in a small crew, jobs would be shared out regardless of title, so a Cook might become a Pilot, or the Carpenter become the Surgeon, as the need arose.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Captain Nathaniel Butler (Boteler), second quarter of C17th, describes the duties of a Quarter-master, stating that the number of Quarter-masters depends on the size of the vessel.  So Quarter-master may be equivalent to "Mate", but not specifically to "First Mate."
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
I think, however, that "Mate", without any other distinction, such as Gunner's Mate etc, probably derives from Master's Mate.  
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
The duties of the Quarter-master appear to be confined to the ship's quarter, i.e "that part of the ship ... that lieth from the steerage room to the transom,"  i.e. the back end.  
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
The Master had the more general responsibility for managing the ship and crew that we associate with Mates.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
From Butler's "Dialogicall Discourse concerning Marine Affaires", 1634;
</kw><br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
"The next office is that of Quarter-masters (of whom there are more or less as the vessel is more or less in burthen).  Their particular duties are to rummage in the hold of the ship on all occasions; to accompany and overlook the Steward when he delivers out the victuals to the Cook and when he serves and pumps the beer; and to take care that he commit no abuse or wastes.  They are also to keep their watches, when the ship's company is quartered; every quarter being to have one Quartermaster at the least in their watch, whether it be quarter watch, when the ship is in harbour and at anchor, or half watch when it is at sea, and in foul weather.  These Quarter-masters are also to take their turn at conning the ship, and to look to him at the helm, that he be diligent in his steering; and to suffer none to be idling in the steerage, that may disturb him and make him careless of his hand."
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
"..the Master.. is to see the ship's company to be duly divided, and quartered for the true performing of their watches and for the trimming and management of her sails upon all occasions ..."  The Master also appoints and supervises the Quarter-masters, and carries out or supervises the routine navigational tasks.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
Old Ged</kw></div><br>
</div>


<div class="PhorumReadNavBlock" style="text-align: left;">
