<div class="PhorumReadMessageBlock">
<div class="PhorumStdBlock">
<div class="PhorumReadBodySubject"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-2">Re: Ship ownership</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Posted by: </kw><strong><a href="http://www.piratesinfo.com/mysql/phorum/profile.php?1,1696"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Aaron Whifflingpin</kw></a></strong><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1"> (---.winn.dial.virgin.net)</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Date: 18 November 2004, 09:35AM</kw></div>
<br>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyText"> 
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Don't be plagued - there is clearly no definitive answer.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
From the bit you quoted,  Monson is partly in agreement with Butler, but Butler allocates the traverse board, and the general supervision of the watch, to the Master.  
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
If the ship had a Master, he could, of course, delegate some or all of his quarter-deck functions to a Quarter-master.  If there were no Master (or Master's Mate) then a Quarter-master would assume some of the Master's duties.
</kw><br>
<br>
<br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Bring back the Bacardi, Darby, please</kw></div><br>
</div>


