<a name="msg-14094"></a>
<div class="PhorumReadMessageBlock">
<div class="PhorumStdBlock">
<div class="PhorumReadBodySubject"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-2">Re: Ship ownership</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Posted by: </kw><strong><a href="http://www.piratesinfo.com/mysql/phorum/profile.php?1,1696"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Aaron Whifflingpin</kw></a></strong><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1"> (---.winn.dial.virgin.net)</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Date: 18 November 2004, 05:15PM</kw></div>
<br>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyText"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3"> Ah, but did they?
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Quick browse of Johnson:
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
First mention of Quarter-master that I found: Lt-Gov of Virginia's proclamation, groups QM  with Lieutenant, Master, Boatswain and Carpenter.
</kw><br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Second mention: listing those that died with Teach, puts QM after Commander, Gunner, boatswain &amp; carpenter:
</kw><br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Third mention: Rackham was Vane's Quartermaster, but there was also a Mate, and Rackham does not appear to be 2ic.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
With one exception, the other references that I found did not assign any particular eminence to the QM.  Captain Lowther's Articles do not assign any bonus share to the QM, while the Master, Doctor, Mate, Gunner &amp; Bosun all get a bonus.  In Lowther's articles, all booty has to be handed over to the QM, but that is consistent with the QM's usual duty of supervising all the goods &amp; stores on the ship.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
HOWEVER,  in life of Capt Roberts, the QM is highly rated.  The pirate articles award the Captain &amp; QM 2 shares, but only 1&amp;1/2 shares to Master, Boatswain &amp; Gunner.  The explanation for this is clearly given; "For the punishment of small offences, which are not provided for by the articles, and which are not of consequence enough to be left to a jury, there is a principal officer among the pirates called the Quartermaster, of the men's own choosing, who claims all authority this way...In short, this officer is trustee for the whole.... [he] acts as a sort of a civil magistrate on board a pirate ship"
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
This function is clearly different from or additional to the usual functions of Quartermaster described by Monson or Butler.  In fact, it is a function that only arises in the pirate world, where each vessel is its own sovereign commonwealth.  The Captain in this situation is the (elected) war leader, the Quartermaster is name given, in this case, to the Chairman or senior civil official. 
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Maybe, in Captain Roberts' crew, the Quartermaster had particular personal qualities that caused him to be elected to the post, and he just kept his old title with a new job.  
</kw><br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Or, maybe the Quartermaster, as a literate officer, might normally rise to this position.  I think, for example, that where a crew became pirates following a mutiny, the more senior officers could be deposed along with the Captain - in which case a junior officer with sufficient knowledge of navigation could become much more important.  Pure speculation - not enough data.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Oh, I only have Cordingly's edition of Johnson, so I guess there may be other examples in a fuller version;  and I may have missed some, anyway.
</kw><br>
  
<br>
<br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
Fetch aft the rum, Darby</kw><br>
<br>
<br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
