<a name="msg-14097"></a>
<div class="PhorumReadMessageBlock">
<div class="PhorumStdBlock">
<div class="PhorumReadBodySubject"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-2">Re: Ship ownership</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Posted by: </kw><strong><a href="http://www.piratesinfo.com/mysql/phorum/profile.php?1,6"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Foxe</kw></a></strong><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1"> (---.winn.dial.virgin.net)</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Date: 19 November 2004, 08:22AM</kw></div>
<br>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyText"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3"> There we go, 
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
of the four known (to us) sets of pirate articles, only one of them mentions quartermasters as being anything special. If the QM was so important why doesn't he even rate an extra 1/4 share in the other sets?
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
To add to the bits from Johnson already mentioned: at rackham's trial the pirate officers are listed "John Rackam Captain, George Fetherston Master, Richard Corner Quarter-Master", probably implying that the master ranked higher than the quartermaster, but certainly not suggesting that the quartermaster was 2IC.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Until more evidence is shown I think it's fair to say that the quartermasters of pirate ships did not hold any particular position of authority in excess of that held by quartermaster's of other ships - ie, they were not second in command, not superior to masters or boatswains as is so often suggested. However, in some cases (though by no means all - let's be clear about this) the Quartermaster did act as the crew's representative, a bridge between the base seamen and the officers - in modern terms a kind of shop steward or union rep. 
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
That seems to be what is indicated by the evidence submitted thus far; the various ship's articles, the narratives contained in Johnson's General History, and the general custom of the sea at that time in history.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Any more sources?
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
.</kw><br>
<br>
<br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
Foxe
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
Historian,  Pirate Dogmatist, Destroyer of Buckets</kw></div><br>
