<a name="msg-14207"></a>
<div class="PhorumReadMessageBlock">
<div class="PhorumStdBlock">
<div class="PhorumReadBodySubject"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-2">Re: Ship ownership</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Posted by: </kw><strong><a href="http://www.piratesinfo.com/mysql/phorum/profile.php?1,6"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Foxe</kw></a></strong><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1"> (---.glfd.dial.virgin.net)</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Date: 29 November 2004, 08:42AM</kw></div>
<br>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyText"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3"> Welcome back Daniel!
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Can you recall exactly what was said of Low's QM? It's a fine point I know, but I'm trying to argue that the QM did not have any extra command, but that his power derived merely from being the representative of the crew, much like a Trade Union rep in a factory now. The TU rep is in some ways the most powerful man, since he can call off work and bring production to standstill, in the same was a QM could (on behalf of the crew) refuse to sail somewhere. On the other hand the TU rep is not usually a high ranking person in the company, and I don't believe the QM was high ranking in himself, only because he was the embodiment of the wishes of the crew as a whole.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
There is a certain amount of indirect evidence (the lack of QMs in some crews for example, or the government proclamations which offer similar or lower rewards for QMs compared with other pirate officers), as well as direct evidence (articles for example) in support of my statement, but I just want to make sure I've got it right.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
Of course, the exact position of officers in any pirate ship might be different. For example, I think in Roberts' ship the QM had a more significatn role than in most others, but since many modern sources work from Johnson's description of the QMs on Roberts' ships that has contributed unfairly to our opinions of their importance.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
In a nutshell, it is my belief that in *most* cases the pirate QM had extra civil duties in addition to the normal duties of a QM on any other ship, and that as the representative of the crew he wielded the power of the masses, but that it was not HIS personally. I also believe that this did not translate into any actual command or rank unexpected of a QM.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
.</kw><br>
<br>
<br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
Foxe
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
Historian,  Pirate Dogmatist, Destroyer of Buckets</kw></div><br>
</div>


