<a name="msg-14219"></a>
<div class="PhorumReadMessageBlock">
<div class="PhorumStdBlock">
<div class="PhorumReadBodySubject"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-2">Re: Ship ownership</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Posted by: </kw><strong><a href="http://www.piratesinfo.com/mysql/phorum/profile.php?1,6"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Foxe</kw></a></strong><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1"> (---.glfd.dial.virgin.net)</kw></div>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyHead"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Date: 30 November 2004, 08:38AM</kw></div>
<br>
<div class="PhorumReadBodyText"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3"> Now to me that's pretty ambiguous.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
To say that someone has twice the sway with the crew as the Captain does is not the same thing as having authority. A popular man of any rank might have more sway than an unpopular captain. It certainly puts him in a position of some measure, but my argument is that QMs did not occupy the position or authority of 2IC as so many modern sources suggest.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
The second quote is interesting, but doesn't really add anything new - in plenty of sources it shows the QM to be responsible for dipensing justice, or at least overseeing it, but without suggesting that he had any actual command unexpected of him. The shooting of deserters is essentially a "civil" duty rather than evidence of command, and that's what I'm really trying to differentiate here. The QMs on pirate vessels seem to have had extra civil duties which QMs on other ships didn't have, but that doesn't mean they had extra command as is often stated in modern books and websites.
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">
.</kw><br>
<br>
<br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
Foxe
</kw><br>
<br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">
Historian,  Pirate Dogmatist, Destroyer of Buckets</kw></div><br>
